<br>
Anyway I'm figuring the best thing for me is to take a dip in the pool in Shadow Haven. Silly me. After a few trips off the edge and practicing my frog-diving, some new toons that were admiring my diving style asked me for some pointers after their own dives. Again, silly me.<br>
<br>
In an attempt to show them what I thought would assist their understanding of their and my differing techniques, I dove in along the narrow axis of the pool and ran my fuzzy little head SMACK into the opposite wall.<br>
<br>
After much kibbitzing with my would-be tadpoles about whether or not I had given myself grievous harm, Valathia comes down to clean the hair out of the gash I'd given myself by effectively smashing my left eyebrow into a rather unyielding surface. <br>
<br>
Time and again Val pleaded with me to go to the Druid and get it looked at, and I every time refused - maintaining that, as the saying goes: &quot;It's just a flesh wound!!&quot;<br>
<br>
Valathia dressed the damage, which appeared to be about the size and shape of that strange white leading-edge of a human's thumbnail. There were a couple of tear-lines perpendicular to it at points, and in all I thought it looked somewhat neat. Being a Vah Shir, I figured I'd just use my paw to staunch the dribble issuing forth from beneath my torn skin. I was neither dizzy nor ill and was in good spirits, bleeding brow notwithstanding.<br>
<br>
Since I felt that scars are something one could wear with pride, I didn't feel the need to submit to a druid's care.  However in order to appease the mothering Valathia, I finally agreed that two hours without a good solid clotting was cause to go visit the Druid camp just down the way.<br>
<br>
Some SIX HOURS LATER waiting at the Druid camp, (and several long illusion-shows from some sort of Caster known as &quot;Disney&quot;) I am at last ushered in to a tent and told to lie back where I can be examined.<br>
<br>
The druid initiate looked me over, saw that I had damaged a sensitive portion of my hide, and said to me,<br>
&quot;Well, it's awful close to your eye. I'm afraid we won't be able to just heal it away. I'll get some thread and my needle set and we'll just have to sew that fuzzy noggin shut before you lose something more valuable than pride and blood.&quot;<br>
<br>
I mumbled my thanks and was glad to have a fur-covered face to hide my chagrin. The good healer was kind enough to administer a small numbing spell and I felt only the vestiges of them suturing my brow like so much wet leather. When finished, he reported that he had sewn 6 tiny knots out of dark green thread, its source I could not determine. I was given an unguent to prevent infection and a light bandage to prevent messiness.<br>
<br>
Daylight had come and Valathia and I thanked the healers, giving them their required tithe and wending our way back to Shadow Haven.<br>
<br>
The moral of the story? When you smack your head in the pool and Val says go to the healers, just go. Don't argue. Just get it over with. <br>
